Like I know--

00:49:02.597 --> 00:49:03.430
STEVEN KOTLER: Yeah.

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:05.857
So yeah, let me--
let's stop there.

00:49:05.857 --> 00:49:07.690
Because if you were
going to say that nobody

00:49:07.690 --> 00:49:09.444
gets to be in flow all the time.

00:49:09.444 --> 00:49:11.110
People come up to me
about once a month,

00:49:11.110 --> 00:49:13.026
and are like, [WHISPERING]
dude, Steven, psst,

00:49:13.026 --> 00:49:14.340
I'm in flow all the time.

00:49:14.340 --> 00:49:15.890
You should study me.

00:49:15.890 --> 00:49:18.047
And this has been
happening for years.

00:49:18.047 --> 00:49:19.880
In the beginning, I
didn't know what to say.

00:49:19.880 --> 00:49:21.670
And now I'm just honest.

00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:23.420
I'm like, absolutely.

00:49:23.420 --> 00:49:24.980
You know, we have
a term for that--

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:26.560
we call that schizophrenia.

00:49:26.560 --> 00:49:28.300
Sometimes we call
that mania, depending.

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:29.770
But it's an either/or.

00:49:29.770 --> 00:49:30.820
Flow is a cycle.

00:49:30.820 --> 00:49:33.070
Herb Benson did a lot of the
foundational neuroscience

00:49:33.070 --> 00:49:34.330
on this.

00:49:34.330 --> 00:49:35.500
And it's a four-part cycle.

00:49:35.500 --> 00:49:37.360
And as you pointed out,
those neurochemicals

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:39.820
that show up in the flow
are expensive for the brain

00:49:39.820 --> 00:49:40.470
to produce.

00:49:40.470 --> 00:49:41.980
They require minerals.

00:49:41.980 --> 00:49:44.065
And some of them
require sunlight.

00:49:44.065 --> 00:49:45.940
And some of them require
vitamins, and foods,

00:49:45.940 --> 00:49:49.000
and blah, blah, blah.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:50.950
So there's a recovery time.

00:49:50.950 --> 00:49:52.810
Norepinephrine and
Dopamine, for example,

00:49:52.810 --> 00:49:54.850
why are Ted Talks
20 minutes long?

00:49:54.850 --> 00:49:57.220
Because these are you two
principal focusing chemicals,

00:49:57.220 --> 00:49:59.560
and they are mostly
exhausted after 20 minutes

00:49:59.560 --> 00:50:00.890
at peak concentration.

00:50:00.890 --> 00:50:02.852
So if you've ever seen
a James Bond movie,

00:50:02.852 --> 00:50:04.810
everything blows up for
the first half an hour,

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:07.455
and then you're bored to death
for the rest of the time.

00:50:07.455 --> 00:50:08.830
It's because you've
exhausted all

00:50:08.830 --> 00:50:11.230
you're focusing feel-good
drugs, and now you've

00:50:11.230 --> 00:50:13.720
just got bad popcorn
in your stomach.

00:50:13.720 --> 00:50:15.760
I mean, literally,
like that feeling.

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:18.400
So yes, on the
backside of flow there

00:50:18.400 --> 00:50:20.500
is a recovery period for sure.

00:50:20.500 --> 00:50:21.460
It's built in.

00:50:21.460 --> 00:50:26.460
So nobody gets to live in
flow as far as we can tell.

00:50:26.460 --> 00:50:28.540
There's some really
interesting work--

00:50:28.540 --> 00:50:32.440
some people often
misconflated enlightenment

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:34.210
with permanent flow.

00:50:34.210 --> 00:50:36.160
There's an idea out
there that enlightenment

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:37.720
might be permanent flow.

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:40.570
We've actually made some
really interesting progress

00:50:40.570 --> 00:50:42.984
on studying so-called
enlightenment.

00:50:42.984 --> 00:50:44.650
And the one thing
that we're pretty sure

00:50:44.650 --> 00:50:46.400
is it doesn't appear
to be permanent flow.

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:48.880
It seems that it takes
the shift in perspective

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:51.580
that you get from flow,
that expansive oneness

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:53.440
with everything that
allows you to access it

00:50:53.440 --> 00:50:56.260
under normal conditions,
but it doesn't seem

00:50:56.260 --> 00:50:57.520
to be a permanent flow state.

00:50:57.520 --> 00:50:58.769
I don't think that's possible.

00:50:58.769 --> 00:51:01.606
Outside a manic episode, I
don't think that's possible.

00:51:01.606 --> 00:51:02.520
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

