00:52:02.840 --> 00:52:04.290
STEVEN KOTLER: I call bullshit.

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:05.604
AUDIENCE: It's BS, OK.

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:11.100
STEVEN KOTLER: What
I've found consistently

00:52:11.100 --> 00:52:12.610
is there a lot of
people out there

00:52:12.610 --> 00:52:17.210
who have a device that measures
one thing or does one thing,

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:19.220
and they want to call it flow.

00:52:19.220 --> 00:52:21.700
So we've got this EEG device
that drives your brainwaves

00:52:21.700 --> 00:52:23.130
to the alpha-theta
borderline, and it's

00:52:23.130 --> 00:52:23.980
going to put you into flow.

00:52:23.980 --> 00:52:25.730
Well no, it's going
to drive your brain

00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:27.460
waves to the alpha-theta
borderline, OK.

00:52:27.460 --> 00:52:31.000
But flow is changes in
network structures, changes

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:32.410
in neural anatomical function.

00:52:32.410 --> 00:52:33.910
It's changes in neurochemistry.

00:52:33.910 --> 00:52:35.980
It's a bunch of
physiological reactions

00:52:35.980 --> 00:52:38.200
that we're just now
starting to maybe measure.

00:52:38.200 --> 00:52:40.630
And nobody's put it all together
in one physiological flow

00:52:40.630 --> 00:52:43.450
detector at this point,
though we are working on one.

00:52:43.450 --> 00:52:46.000
But anytime I hear a single
correlate hypothesis--

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:48.140
it takes your brain
waves, it does this--

00:52:48.140 --> 00:52:51.655
and calling it flow, to me,
I don't understand that.

00:52:51.655 --> 00:52:53.030
I don't understand
why people are

00:52:53.030 --> 00:52:57.140
doing that when we know flow has
total shift in brain function.

00:52:57.140 --> 00:52:58.940
So that's first of all.

00:52:58.940 --> 00:53:02.080
When it comes to sound,
though I have friends Will

00:53:02.080 --> 00:53:04.870
Henshall at Focus
Will, Brain FM,

00:53:04.870 --> 00:53:06.850
there are some really
interesting groups

00:53:06.850 --> 00:53:10.060
doing really good work
on sound and flow.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:13.390
My friend Kris Berkner who
runs Advanced Brain Monitoring

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:15.730
in Carlsbad, California,
she is the person

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:19.600
who teamed up with the DOD to
do the flow in the accelerated

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:20.837
learning stuff.

00:53:20.837 --> 00:53:21.670
She give a Ted Talk.

00:53:21.670 --> 00:53:22.990
You can find that online.

00:53:22.990 --> 00:53:25.990
One of the things they did is
they looked at binaural beats.

00:53:25.990 --> 00:53:28.680
There were 400 companies doing
sound with binaural beats.

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:30.763
And it's supposed to put
you in flow and whatever.

00:53:33.250 --> 00:53:36.220
They make just about
the best EEG measurement

00:53:36.220 --> 00:53:39.970
device in the world,
I think, and they

00:53:39.970 --> 00:53:42.130
took every binaural beats
program they could find

00:53:42.130 --> 00:53:45.100
and looked for any consistent
neurological shift, found

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:46.580
nothing that was consistent.

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:50.020
So I'm not saying that there
is this technology out there--

00:53:50.020 --> 00:53:52.900
sooner or later, somebody is
going to crack that, right?

00:53:52.900 --> 00:53:57.280
We know from Apple's work with
Sonos that the power of music

00:53:57.280 --> 00:54:00.990
is really amazing in terms of
its ability to shift conscious.

00:54:00.990 --> 00:54:03.400
So there's definitely
something there.

00:54:03.400 --> 00:54:09.952
But we're not there yet, I
don't think, nothing I've seen.

00:54:09.952 --> 00:54:11.410
There are probably
people out there

00:54:11.410 --> 00:54:14.116
would breakthrough technology
that tell me I'm lying

00:54:14.116 --> 00:54:14.740
and don't know.

00:54:14.740 --> 00:54:16.900
But I haven't seen
anything that I'm

00:54:16.900 --> 00:54:18.910
comfortable with that
I think does that yet.

00:54:18.910 --> 00:54:20.410
I think we're getting
closer though.

00:54:20.410 --> 00:54:23.740
And I think all this stuff is
on exponential growth curves.

00:54:23.740 --> 00:54:27.520
So you know what seemed
absolutely ridiculous

00:54:27.520 --> 00:54:29.080
three years ago,
you are going to get

00:54:29.080 --> 00:54:31.337
in two years, three years.

00:54:31.337 --> 00:54:32.170
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:32.170 --> 00:54:34.616
STEVEN KOTLER: Sure.

00:54:34.616 --> 00:54:36.240
AUDIENCE: All right,
thanks for coming.

00:54:36.240 --> 00:54:38.115
From your comments, it
sounds like you're not

00:54:38.115 --> 00:54:40.980
a big fan of open office plans.

00:54:40.980 --> 00:54:44.550
But open office plans are a
super big fad around here.

00:54:44.550 --> 00:54:48.420
So my request to you
is please rescue us.

00:54:48.420 --> 00:54:49.580
What can you do for us?

00:54:49.580 --> 00:54:50.470
STEVEN KOTLER: Yeah.

00:54:50.470 --> 00:54:53.040
It's a fair point.

00:54:53.040 --> 00:54:54.270
And you're not the only one.

00:54:54.270 --> 00:54:56.310
A couple of years ago,
when Facebook decided

00:54:56.310 --> 00:54:58.200
they were going to do away
with desks entirely and put

00:54:58.200 --> 00:55:00.616
everybody on walking desks,
facing each other in a circle.

00:55:00.616 --> 00:55:03.033
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:04.692 --> 00:55:06.650
I don't know if that's
true or not, by the way.

00:55:06.650 --> 00:55:10.270
But I just heard it, and I was
like what a disaster for flow.

00:55:10.270 --> 00:55:14.830
That said, open office plans can
be really good for group flow,

00:55:14.830 --> 00:55:15.820
depending.

00:55:15.820 --> 00:55:17.770
They have their purpose.

00:55:17.770 --> 00:55:21.010
The companies that I'm
seeing that are doing this

00:55:21.010 --> 00:55:22.660
are building--

00:55:22.660 --> 00:55:26.402
any of the co-work spaces
that you're seeing pop up,

00:55:26.402 --> 00:55:28.360
they have little phone
booth rooms that anybody

00:55:28.360 --> 00:55:30.130
can go into and shut
the door, and it's

00:55:30.130 --> 00:55:31.580
a private little office.

00:55:31.580 --> 00:55:34.570
So I'm seeing a lot of companies
that like open office plans

00:55:34.570 --> 00:55:37.840
start to build in silence
pods, where you can just

00:55:37.840 --> 00:55:41.110
close yourself in and
lock yourself off.

00:55:41.110 --> 00:55:45.310
And equally important is you've
got to have your conversations

00:55:45.310 --> 00:55:47.680
about this.

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:50.200
If you've got a
manager, and they're not

00:55:50.200 --> 00:55:51.951
into this whole idea
of what you're doing.

00:55:51.951 --> 00:55:54.158
And suddenly you're going
off from 90 to 120 minutes,

00:55:54.158 --> 00:55:56.560
and you're coming back with
something like I was in flow,

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:58.690
you're going to be fired.

00:55:58.690 --> 00:56:01.300
So it's got to be
done loud, I think.

00:56:01.300 --> 00:56:03.700
People have to understand
why this is mandatory.

00:56:03.700 --> 00:56:06.710
But I think open office
plans, ultimately,

00:56:06.710 --> 00:56:10.030
I think we're going to
start to see them go away.

00:56:10.030 --> 00:56:12.520
And I think some of
this is just that we're

00:56:12.520 --> 00:56:14.350
going to be 3D printing
office buildings,

00:56:14.350 --> 00:56:16.390
and we get complexity for free.

00:56:16.390 --> 00:56:18.670
So suddenly it's not
going to be cost efficient

00:56:18.670 --> 00:56:20.350
to put everybody in cubicles.

00:56:20.350 --> 00:56:21.700
We're going to being able
to build whole offices,

00:56:21.700 --> 00:56:23.637
and I think the problem's
going to get solved.

00:56:23.637 --> 00:56:25.970
I think it's a money issue
less than an open office plan

00:56:25.970 --> 00:56:27.040
issue at this point.

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:30.280
But yeah, they are
disasters for flow.

00:56:34.980 --> 00:56:38.940
AUDIENCE: So you talked
about the psychedelic drugs.

00:56:38.940 --> 00:56:40.090
But I'm curious.

00:56:40.090 --> 00:56:44.310
Are there studies seeing
how different drugs simulate

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:47.060
the flow state, like
cocaine, marijuana.

00:56:50.582 --> 00:56:52.540
STEVEN KOTLER: The
neurochemicals, the big five

00:56:52.540 --> 00:56:58.090
neurochemicals, every time
you have a neurochemical--

00:56:58.090 --> 00:57:02.080
you have an endogenous
and exogenous chemical,

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:05.800
so the body produces endorphins.

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:08.800
These are our natural opiates.

00:57:08.800 --> 00:57:14.680
So flow is essentially
dopamine, which is cocaine.

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:16.960
Whenever you use
cocaine, all that happens

00:57:16.960 --> 00:57:19.270
is the brain releases
a bunch of dopamine,

00:57:19.270 --> 00:57:22.210
and it blocks its re-uptake.

00:57:22.210 --> 00:57:23.680
You get a little serotonin.

00:57:23.680 --> 00:57:28.640
That's ecstasy at one
pathway or LSD in another.

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:31.680
anandamide, which,
as you said, is THC.

00:57:31.680 --> 00:57:35.290
Norepinephrine is
essentially speed.

00:57:35.290 --> 00:57:37.307
I don't know what
I'm forgetting here.

00:57:37.307 --> 00:57:38.890
But the point is you
actually couldn't

00:57:38.890 --> 00:57:40.540
cocktail those drugs
on the street, which

00:57:40.540 --> 00:57:41.360
is really interesting.

00:57:41.360 --> 00:57:42.400
Some of them counteract.

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:46.010
You're going to end up dead
or in a coma if you try.

00:57:46.010 --> 00:57:49.120
What's cool is the brain can
cocktail them all naturally

00:57:49.120 --> 00:57:52.405
and you don't tend--

00:57:52.405 --> 00:57:54.370
I mean, you know,
flow has a dark side.

00:57:54.370 --> 00:57:55.850
It's a very sticky state.

00:57:55.850 --> 00:57:59.140
It's very addictive.

00:57:59.140 --> 00:58:01.972
Csikszentmihalyi said flow
is different than most

00:58:01.972 --> 00:58:02.680
other addictions.

00:58:02.680 --> 00:58:04.840
Most other addictions
lead backwards.

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:07.727
Flow, because you're always
extending your skills,

00:58:07.727 --> 00:58:10.060
because you're walking up
that challange skills balance,

00:58:10.060 --> 00:58:12.020
is an addiction
that leads forward.

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:15.010
But if you have a
high flow lifestyle--

00:58:15.010 --> 00:58:18.760
the Navy SEALs, who we do some
work, when the Navy SEALs stop

00:58:18.760 --> 00:58:21.070
being Navy SEALs, when an
action sport athlete stops

00:58:21.070 --> 00:58:24.340
being an action sport
athlete, when a rock star

00:58:24.340 --> 00:58:26.240
stops being a rock star--

00:58:26.240 --> 00:58:30.820
These are massively difficult
transitions to handle.

00:58:30.820 --> 00:58:33.029
And a lot of what we're
seeing, for example,

00:58:33.029 --> 00:58:35.320
in soldiers returning from
combat and things like that,

00:58:35.320 --> 00:58:38.410
is these are such high flow
environments, that compared

00:58:38.410 --> 00:58:40.750
to regular life, it's
really difficult.

00:58:40.750 --> 00:58:42.989
And that's a big portion
of the difficulty.

00:58:42.989 --> 00:58:44.530
And we're doing some
work around that

00:58:44.530 --> 00:58:46.540
to try to see what
we can learn there.

00:58:46.540 --> 00:58:50.875
There's a long way to go,
but we're poking at it.

00:58:50.875 --> 00:58:53.202
Anybody else?

00:58:53.202 --> 00:58:55.610
AUDIENCE: Yeah, two more
questions both from the Dory.

00:58:55.610 --> 00:58:59.832
The first one is about
the concept of flow hike--

00:58:59.832 --> 00:59:01.040
STEVEN KOTLER: [LAUGHING] OK.

00:59:01.040 --> 00:59:03.320
AUDIENCE: --that was
addressed on our podcast.

00:59:03.320 --> 00:59:06.170
How can we translate
flow states that we

00:59:06.170 --> 00:59:12.260
achieve through athletic
pursuits to everyday life?

00:59:12.260 --> 00:59:15.016
STEVEN KOTLER: So
part of that answer--

00:59:15.016 --> 00:59:18.679
do they want me to break down
the flow hike or was that--

00:59:18.679 --> 00:59:20.720
AUDIENCE: Basically, if
I understand the question

00:59:20.720 --> 00:59:28.350
correctly, how we can sort
of use the flow hike online.

00:59:28.350 --> 00:59:29.100
STEVEN KOTLER: OK.

00:59:31.730 --> 00:59:34.940
So there's a couple
of different answers.

00:59:34.940 --> 00:59:39.470
The first answer is flow is
a focusing skill essentially.

00:59:39.470 --> 00:59:42.430
Whoever said it was
like meditation 101,

00:59:42.430 --> 00:59:44.220
there's a lot of
fundamentals there.

00:59:44.220 --> 00:59:48.270
We train people in mindfulness
because flow follows focus.

00:59:48.270 --> 00:59:52.219
So you want to drive that
focus into the present tense.

00:59:52.219 --> 00:59:53.010
How did I get here?

00:59:53.010 --> 00:59:54.311
What did you ask me?

00:59:54.311 --> 00:59:55.310
I totally lost my place.

00:59:55.310 --> 00:59:55.976
I looked at you.

00:59:55.976 --> 00:59:57.770
I did the meditation thing.

00:59:57.770 --> 00:59:59.002
What was the question?

00:59:59.002 --> 01:00:01.210
AUDIENCE: Flow hike or flow
through athletic pursuits

01:00:01.210 --> 01:00:01.918
in everyday life.

01:00:01.918 --> 01:00:05.470
STEVEN KOTLER: Flow
through athletic pursuits,

01:00:05.470 --> 01:00:07.070
it tends to translate.

01:00:07.070 --> 01:00:11.480
so the flow training that
I get while skiing helps me

01:00:11.480 --> 01:00:12.470
as a writer.

01:00:12.470 --> 01:00:14.240
It's the same kind of focus.

01:00:14.240 --> 01:00:17.600
So whenever you're training
that, you're training that--

01:00:17.600 --> 01:00:21.820
one is the athletic pursuits
will just naturally bleed over

01:00:21.820 --> 01:00:23.610
into your everyday life.

01:00:23.610 --> 01:00:26.420
So in other words, the more flow
you get, the more flow you get.

01:00:26.420 --> 01:00:27.920
That's across the boards.

01:00:27.920 --> 01:00:31.310
The flow hike is not an
athletic pursuit hike.

01:00:31.310 --> 01:00:32.840
It's actually a daily flow.

01:00:32.840 --> 01:00:35.060
Like you asked about
the neurobiology, right.

01:00:35.060 --> 01:00:38.070
So this is a hike
I use every day.

01:00:38.070 --> 01:00:38.730
I wake up.

01:00:38.730 --> 01:00:40.563
I start writing at 4
o'clock in the morning.

01:00:40.563 --> 01:00:41.990
I write from 4:00 till 8:00 AM.

01:00:41.990 --> 01:00:44.390
And at 8:00 AM, I take
my dogs for a hike.

01:00:44.390 --> 01:00:48.194
And it's a hike specifically
designed to put me into flow.

01:00:48.194 --> 01:00:50.360
Meaning if my writing session
was really unpleasant,

01:00:50.360 --> 01:00:51.830
if I was struggling
a bunch, this

01:00:51.830 --> 01:00:53.710
is going to put me into
flow on the back end.

01:00:53.710 --> 01:00:56.480
And so when I come back to
work, I'll feel refreshed.

01:00:56.480 --> 01:00:59.360
And [INAUDIBLE] flow state is
a good way to reset my system.

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:02.750
But what I do is I start off
and I walk uphill very slowly

01:01:02.750 --> 01:01:04.670
for 20 to 25 minutes.

01:01:04.670 --> 01:01:07.730
Low grade physical activity
for about 20 to 25 minutes

01:01:07.730 --> 01:01:10.302
will produce exercise-induced
transient hypo-frontality.

01:01:10.302 --> 01:01:12.260
It's going to deactivate
the prefrontal cortex.

01:01:12.260 --> 01:01:13.100
We all know this, right?

01:01:13.100 --> 01:01:14.000
You go to the gym.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:15.860
You workout for
about 20, 25 minutes.

01:01:15.860 --> 01:01:17.795
It gets quiet upstairs.

01:01:17.795 --> 01:01:19.790
I then run uphill.

01:01:19.790 --> 01:01:20.850
I run up cliff faces.

01:01:20.850 --> 01:01:22.940
Or you could just
sprint if you want.

01:01:22.940 --> 01:01:24.440
And I do it for
about five minutes

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:27.630
or until I'm in pain basically.

01:01:27.630 --> 01:01:29.450
And then I sort of slow it down.

01:01:29.450 --> 01:01:32.150
And you will get
endorphins and anandamide,

01:01:32.150 --> 01:01:35.150
which are pain relievers
among other things.

01:01:35.150 --> 01:01:38.390
And then, I turned around
and I run back downhill,

01:01:38.390 --> 01:01:40.850
trying to move my feet faster
than they would normally

01:01:40.850 --> 01:01:42.260
move without gravity.

01:01:42.260 --> 01:01:44.960
So they are big leaps
down that mountain.

01:01:44.960 --> 01:01:48.140
Whenever you take a
risk, you get dopamine.

01:01:48.140 --> 01:01:50.590
And so by the time I'm
back down on my path

01:01:50.590 --> 01:01:55.270
and I'm walking home, I've
mimicked essentially a bunch

01:01:55.270 --> 01:01:56.680
of the neurobiology of flow.

01:01:56.680 --> 01:01:57.790
It's not 100%.

01:01:57.790 --> 01:01:59.750
It doesn't work all the time.

01:01:59.750 --> 01:02:02.840
But pretty much it'll put you
into a low grade flow state.

01:02:02.840 --> 01:02:05.330
And I do this between
work sessions.

01:02:05.330 --> 01:02:08.180
And it takes about 45 minutes.

01:02:08.180 --> 01:02:11.027
And I try to do my problem
solving on the way home

01:02:11.027 --> 01:02:12.610
because I'm in a low
grade flow state,

01:02:12.610 --> 01:02:15.068
and I've got heightened learning
and creativity and pattern

01:02:15.068 --> 01:02:15.641
recognition.

01:02:15.641 --> 01:02:17.140
And so if there was
something that I

01:02:17.140 --> 01:02:18.940
wasn't doing in my writing--

01:02:18.940 --> 01:02:20.620
I got stuck somewhere--

01:02:20.620 --> 01:02:22.660
that's when I try to
solve it because I

01:02:22.660 --> 01:02:24.790
know I'm going to be in
a low grade flow state.

01:02:24.790 --> 01:02:26.620
I think that's a
great place to end.

01:02:26.620 --> 01:02:27.760
Thanks, guys.

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:30.510
[APPLAUSE]

